TY  - JOUR
AU  - Kaltenbrunner, Georg
AU  - Lochstoer, Lars A.
T1  - Long-Run Risk through Consumption Smoothing
PY  - 2010
Y1  - 2010/08/01
DO  - 10.1093/rfs/hhq033
JO  - The Review of Financial Studies
JA  - Rev Financ Stud
VL  - 23
IS  - 8
SP  - 3190
EP  - 3224
SN  - 0893-9454
AB  - We examine how long-run consumption risk arises endogenously in a standard production economy model where the representative agent has Epstein–Zin preferences. We show that even when technology growth is i.i.d., optimal consumption smoothing induces long-run risk—highly persistent variation in expected consumption growth. As a consequence, the model can account for a high price of risk, although both consumption growth volatility and the coefficient of relative risk aversion are low. The asset pricing implications of endogenous long-run risk depend crucially on the persistence of technology shocks and investors’ preference for the timing of resolution of uncertainty. (JEL E21, E23, E30, G12)
Y2  - 3/26/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rfs/hhq033
ER  - 



