T1  - The Representative Agent of an Economy with External Habit Formation and Heterogeneous Risk Aversion
PY  - 2010
Y1  - 2010/08/01
DO  - 10.1093/rfs/hhq029
JO  - The Review of Financial Studies
JA  - Rev Financ Stud
VL  - 23
IS  - 8
SP  - 3017
EP  - 3047
SN  - 0893-9454
AB  - In this article, we derive an analytic expression for the representative agent of a large class of economies populated by agents with “catching up with the Joneses” preferences, but who exhibit heterogeneous risk aversion. As Chan and Kogan (2002) show numerically, the representative agent has stochastic risk that moves countercyclically to the state variable. However, we show that heterogeneity of risk aversion alone is insuﬀicient for explaining empirical regularities—namely the variability of the Sharpe ratio—that Campbell and Cochrane (1999) obtain in a model of a representative agent with stochastic risk aversion. 
Y2  - 3/26/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rfs/hhq029
ER  - 



